      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">A 55-year-old man from a rural community in the Thar Desert presents with persistent fever, cough, and weight loss. He also reports painful red nodules on his shins and joint pains. Chest radiography reveals hilar lymphadenopathy. Intradermal testing with a regional fungal antigen is positive. What is the most likely diagnosis?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2240824",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 35681,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Answer: A. Coccidioidomycosis</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Explanation</strong>:&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The patient presents with a constellation of symptoms strongly suggestive of coccidioidomycosis:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Persistent fever, cough, and weight loss are consistent with pulmonary involvement in systemic mycoses.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The report of painful red nodules on his shins is highly indicative of erythema nodosum, which is listed as a skin lesion associated with coccidioidomycosis.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Joint pains (arthralgia) are also a recognised feature of coccidioidomycosis, sometimes referred to as \"desert rheumatism\" or \"valley fever\".</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Chest radiography revealing hilar lymphadenopathy supports pulmonary involvement, which is the most common form of coccidioidomycosis.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The positive intradermal testing with a regional fungal antigen points towards a geographically specific fungal infection. Coccidioidomycosis is diagnosed in part by skin tests demonstrating delayed-type hypersensitivity. Although the sources specify endemic areas primarily in the USA and Mexico, the association of \"desert rheumatism\" with the clinical picture and the positive skin test make this the most likely option.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Other Options:</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Option B. Cryptococcosis</strong>:&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>While Cryptococcus can cause pulmonary infections and disseminate, it typically presents with meningitis, particularly in immunocompromised individuals. Skin lesions can occur, but erythema nodosum and joint pains are not characteristic features.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Option C. Histoplasmosis</strong>:&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Histoplasmosis also presents with pulmonary symptoms and can cause hilar lymphadenopathy. Disseminated forms can affect various organs. However, erythema nodosum is not as strongly associated with histoplasmosis as it is with coccidioidomycosis, and the described endemic areas in the sources are the Ohio and Mississippi River valleys, not the Thar Desert.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Option D. Aspergillosis</strong>:&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Aspergillosis typically affects immunocompromised individuals or those with pre-existing lung conditions. While pulmonary manifestations are common, erythema nodosum and joint pains are not typical presenting features.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Educational Objective:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The combination of pulmonary symptoms, erythema nodosum, arthralgia, and hilar lymphadenopathy, along with a positive regional fungal skin test in a patient from a desert region, strongly suggests coccidioidomycosis.</p>",
